{"cursor":"13859","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox person |image = |imagesize =\n| name = MÃ¡rta MÃ©szÃ¡ros birth_date = birth_place = Budapest, Hungary death_date\n| = death_place = othername = occupation = Film director Screenwriter\n| yearsactive = 1954âpresent\n}}\n\n'MÃ¡rta MÃ©szÃ¡ros' (born September 19, 1931) is a Hungarian screenwriter and film\ndirector. Daughter of Laszlo MÃ©szÃ¡ros, a sculptor, MÃ©szÃ¡ros began her career\nworking in documentary film and made 25 documentary shorts over the span of ten\nyears, before making her first feature film [[Eltavozott nap]] ([[The Girl (1968\nfilm)|The Girl]]), which was released in 1968. The first feature film directed by a woman in the history of\nHungarian cinema and the winner of the Special Prize of the Jury of\nthe International Film Festival in Valladolid.\n\nHer films often combine autobiographical details with documentary footage and\ndeal with the denial of a biographical past, lying and it's consequences, and\nthe problematics of gender. MÃ©szÃ¡ros heroines are often from fragmented\nfamilies: young girls seeking their missing parents (The Girl) or middle aged\nsingle women hoping to adopt a child ([[Adoption]]).\n\nAlthough MÃ©szÃ¡ros has made over fifteen feature films she is probably best known\nfor her film [[Diary for My Children]] (1984), which won the Grand-Prix Award at\nthe Cannes Film Festival and is the first film in a trilogy of autobiographical\nfilms that also includes [[Diary for my Lovers]] (1987), and [[Diary for my\nFather and Mother]] (1990).\n\nMÃ©szÃ¡ros is also the winner of the Golden Bear and Silver Bear awards at the\nBerlinale, Golden medal at the Chicago International Film Festival, Silver Shell\nat the San Sebastian International Film Festival, and the FIPRESCI Prize at the\nCannes Film Festival. In 1991 he was a member of the jury at the 17th Moscow\nInternational Film Festival.\n","linknr":215,"url":"Márta_Mészáros","recorded":1375072521,"link